# Presentation Slide Rules

## Generation workflow (what the agent does when asked to "generate the slides")

The user is only expected to drop **paper files** (the source PDF, and
optionally `.tex` / `.bib` / supplementary material) into `Paper_files/`.
Everything else is the agent's job. When the user asks you to generate,
update, or rebuild the slides, you **must** run this full pipeline, in order:

1. **Read `Paper_files/`.** Inventory what the user dropped. The paper PDF is
   the canonical source of truth for content and figures. Read it (and any
   accompanying `.tex` source if present) to understand the paper's
   structure, claims, and which figures matter for the talk.
2. **Extract the figures the slides will need into `Extracted_figures/`.**
   Do not ask the user to pre-extract figures. Use PyMuPDF (already a
   dependency, see `requirements.txt`) or equivalent to pull the relevant
   embedded images / figure regions out of the paper PDF and save them as
   PNG / JPG files in `Extracted_figures/` with descriptive filenames
   (e.g. `architecture.png`, `results_table.png`). If the user **did** drop
   pre-extracted figure files into `Paper_files/`, prefer those and copy
   them into `Extracted_figures/` as well. After this step,
   `Extracted_figures/` holds everything the deck needs.
3. **Modify `presentation.tex`.** Edit the title / author / date and fill
   the body frames with slide content that reflects the paper. Reference
   figures by **filename only** via `\includegraphics{figure_name}`
   (no path prefix); `\graphicspath` takes care of the lookup. Keep a
   `\note{...}` on the line immediately after every `\end{frame}`.
4. **Compile the PDF.** Run
   `latexmk -pdf -interaction=nonstopmode presentation.tex`.
5. **Build the PPTX.** Run `python3 beamer_to_pptx.py presentation.tex`.
   The converter reads the just-compiled PDF for high-fidelity cropping
   of TikZ / tables, and it *also* copies any still-uncopied figures into
   `Extracted_figures/` as a safety net.

Always recompile the PDF (step 4) **after** any `.tex` edit and **before**
rebuilding the PPTX (step 5), because the converter uses the PDF for
high-fidelity cropping.

## Figure discovery

- **Figures are not "text only"** - `presentation.tex` references them by
  **filename** via `\includegraphics{...}`. The search order is set by
  `\graphicspath` in the preamble: `Extracted_figures/`, then
  `Paper_files/`, then `Assets/`, then the repo root.
- **The canonical figure store is `Extracted_figures/`.** That's where the
  agent writes figures it pulled out of the paper PDF, and where the
  converter copies any other referenced figures.
- **When a figure seems missing** - check `Extracted_figures/` first. If
  it isn't there yet, extract it from the paper PDF in `Paper_files/` and
  save it into `Extracted_figures/`. Do not tell the user to go do that by
  hand.
- **If the user pre-dropped figure files in `Paper_files/`**, treat them as
  hints about what the user considers important and copy them into
  `Extracted_figures/` (the converter will also do this on its next run).

## Project layout

- `presentation.tex` - main Beamer source. `\graphicspath` is
  `{Extracted_figures/}{Paper_files/}{Assets/}`, so figures are referenced
  by filename only.
- `Paper_files/` - **user-populated; starts empty.** The one place the user
  drops the paper. Typically contains the paper PDF plus any optional
  `.tex` / `.bib` / supplementary files. The user is *not* expected to
  extract figures by hand; the agent does that.
- `Extracted_figures/` - **agent- and converter-populated; starts empty.**
  Holds:
  - Figures the agent extracts from the paper PDF during slide generation.
  - Copies of every `\includegraphics` source file the converter sees.
  - Auto-cropped TikZ/table PNGs named `slide_content_<N>.png`
    (git-ignored).
  Do not instruct users to hand-copy files into this folder.
- `Assets/` - logo, banner, and any reusable graphics. The footer logo
  defaults to `Assets/logo.jpg` and is **not** copied into
  `Extracted_figures/` (it's chrome, not slide content).
- `beamer_to_pptx.py` - single-script converter: `.tex` (+ optional `.pdf`)
  into an editable `.pptx`. Copies referenced figures into
  `Extracted_figures/` and writes its TikZ/table crops there too.

## Formatting

- **Bold as leading labels only**: Use `\textbf{Label}:` at the start of
  bullets. Never bold mid-sentence.
- **Consistent bold**: Every bullet in a slide must follow the same
  pattern. If one bullet has a bold label, all bullets on that slide
  should too.
- **No em dashes**: Do not use `---` (em dash). Use commas, semicolons, or
  colons instead.

## Content

- **Tight bullets (when you edit `presentation.tex`)**: You **must** keep
  each body `\item` **short** (one line on 16:9 when possible; no
  paragraph-style items). You **must** put paragraphs of detail in
  `\note{...}` after `\end{frame}`, or split into sub-bullets. Long
  bullets mean the slide is doing the speaker's job; the slide headlines,
  the notes explain.
- **Concise bullets**: Keep slides readable. If a slide feels overwhelming,
  trim content or split into sub-bullets.
- **Sub-bullets for multi-part points**: Break compound ideas into
  sub-bullets rather than one long sentence.
- **Speaker notes are default**: Every frame must be followed by a
  `\note{...}` block on the line immediately after `\end{frame}`. The
  converter reads these and writes them to the PPTX Notes pane.
- **Speaker notes as bullets**: Use bullet-like phrasing in `\note{...}`
  when transitioning between topics or when it improves clarity.
- **Explain abbreviations**: When an abbreviation appears in `\note{...}`,
  spell it out in parentheses on first use (e.g., "CNN (Convolutional
  Neural Network)").
- **Avoid overly bold claims**: Soften absolute language (e.g., "do not
  target" instead of "none target").
- **Lead with top results**: In results slides, highlight the
  best-performing model first, not baselines or outliers.
- **Include key variable comparisons** on each results slide where
  relevant (e.g., frame rate differences).
- **Remove distracting outliers**: Omit odd or unrepresentative data
  points that distract from the main message.

## Layout

- **Image beside text**: Use `\begin{columns}[T]` with left column
  ~0.50\textwidth (text) and right column ~0.47\textwidth (figure). Do
  not place figures below text.
- **Text above footer**: Keep body text from overlapping the footer. Use
  `\vspace{-0.4em}` at frame start; limit figure height (e.g.,
  `height=0.58\textheight`); use `{\small ...}` for dense slides.
- **Figures by filename only**: Because of `\graphicspath`, write
  `\includegraphics{figure1}` rather than
  `\includegraphics{Paper_files/figure1}` or
  `\includegraphics{Extracted_figures/figure1}`.

## Style

- **Sub-bullet color**: All bullet levels must use the same accent color.
  Override Beamer defaults if needed.
- **Logo default**: The footer logo is enabled by default
  (`\renewcommand{\mylogo}{...}` uncommented) and points to
  `Assets/logo.jpg`. Prefer JPG for the footer logo when available.
- **Slide naming**: Use descriptive, audience-friendly titles (e.g.,
  "Situation recognition" over "Factor prediction").

## Tables and TikZ

- The converter falls back to image rasterization for `\begin{tabular}`
  and `\begin{tikzpicture}`.
- Cropping is driven by the PDF's vector drawings (booktabs rule lines,
  TikZ paths) and embedded image rects, not by whitespace heuristics.
  Keep surrounding captions / bullet text out of the same horizontal band
  as the table so the clip stays tight.
- When a table shares a slide with bullet text, the converter snaps the
  crop to the table's bottom rule line - do not place explanatory prose
  immediately under a table that is meant to be extracted as an image;
  put it in `\note{...}` or in a separate frame.
